library(gtsummary)   # tables

Dataset

Dataset: crp2.csv

Description: 120 patients admitted to intensive care (ICU) with sepsis. C-reactive protein (CRP) is a marker of inflammation and, potentially, a marker of sepsis resolution. CRP was measured over 6 days (crp1,â¦crp6) or until discharge/death (discharge_r).

Other variables:

  • SAPS - severity score measured within the first 24h in the ICU

  • age - age at admission

  • SEX - Male / Female

  • SEPSIS - category of sepsis (Sepsis/Severe Sepsis/Septic Shock)

  • antib_1h - was antibiotherapy administer within the first hour in ICU (No/Yes)

Letâs load the data and create a summary table

Changing the data structure

Wide to long

crp.Data <- pivot_longer(data = crp.Data.wide, 
                         cols = c(crp1, crp2, crp3, crp4, crp5, crp6), #cols = crp1:crp6 
                         names_to = "day", 
                         names_transform = list(day = as.numeric), #day as number 
                         values_to = "crp", 
                         names_prefix = "crp", 
                         values_drop_na=TRUE)

Long to wide

crp.Data.wide <- pivot_wider(crp.Data, 
                             names_from = "day", 
                             values_from=crp )

Plotting longitudinal data

Spaghetti plot

#basic plot 
ggplot(data = crp.Data, 
       aes(x=day, y=crp, group=ID)) + 
  geom_line()

#advanced with mean profile line 
ggplot(data = crp.Data,
       aes(x=day, y=crp, group=ID)) + 
  geom_line(alpha=.1) + #transparency to lines 
  scale_x_continuous(breaks=c(1:6)) + #x-axis 1,2...,6 
  labs(title="CRP in sepsis patients in ICU", x = "Time (days)", y = "CRP") + 
  stat_summary(fun=mean, na.rm=T, #adds the means by year 
               aes(group="none"),
geom="line", lwd=2, show.legend = F) + 
  stat_summary(fun.data=mean_cl_boot, #adds the 95%CI 
               aes(group="none"), 
               geom="errorbar", 
               lwd=1, 
               width=.1,
show.legend = F)

#advanced with a smooth trend line 
ggplot(data = crp.Data, 
       aes(x=day, y=crp, group=ID)) + 
  geom_line(alpha=.1) + #transparency to lines 
  scale_x_continuous(breaks=c(1:6)) + #x-axis 1,2...,6 
  labs(title="CRP in sepsis patients in ICU", x = "Time (days)", y = "CRP") +
geom_smooth(method = loess, #adds a smooth line 
            aes(group="none"), #otherwise plots 1 line per ID 
            se=T, # 95% confidence band 
            fill = "green", #colour of conf band
            color="blue") + #colour of the line
  theme_bw() #theme
`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

Violin plot

#geom_violin will do the job
ggplot(crp.Data, 
       aes(x=as.factor(day), y=crp)) + 
  geom_violin() + 
  geom_boxplot(width = 0.1, outlier.colour = "blue") + #boxplot inside
  theme_classic()

Binary outcome and continuous time

The plot below gives you a glimpse of the data when you have a categorical outcome over a continuous time.

bk.Data <- read.csv("https://www.dropbox.com/s/1maznm125j7vm5t/bk.csv?dl=1") 
bk.Data$bk <-ifelse(bk.Data$bk==1, "BK infection", "No BK infection")

ggplot(data = bk.Data[1:200,],   #select just a few patients
       aes(x=time, y=as.factor(ID), colour=bk)) + 
  scale_colour_manual(values = c("No BK infection" = "black", 
                                 "BK infection" = "blue")) + 
  geom_point(alpha=.5) + 
  geom_line(aes(group=ID), alpha=.3) + 
  theme_minimal()

Categorical outcome and discrete time .

#create categories for CKR
new.CKR <- crp.Data %>% 
  mutate(crp.cat = ifelse(crp<10, "crp<10",
                             ifelse(crp<30, "10<crp<30", 
                                           "crp>30"))) %>% 
  mutate(crp.cat=factor(crp.cat, 
                           levels=c("crp<10","10<crp<30", 
                                    "crp>30")))

#produce the percentages of patients in each group by day
  table.new.CKR <- new.CKR %>% 
    select(c("crp.cat", "day")) %>% 
    count(day, crp.cat) %>% 
    group_by(day) %>% 
    mutate(percentage = n / sum(n) * 100)
    
ggplot(table.new.CKR, 
       aes(x=day, y=crp.cat, fill=percentage)) + 
  scale_fill_gradient(low = "white", high = "red") + 
  geom_tile()

The alluvial plots can also be used to plot these data.

library(ggalluvial)

freq_table_long <- new.CKR %>%
  pivot_wider(id_cols = ID, 
              names_from = day, 
              values_from = crp.cat, 
              names_prefix = "Day") %>%
  count(Day1, Day2, Day3) %>%  
  mutate(id = row_number())

freq_table_long2 <- gather(freq_table_long, value, key, -n, -id) %>% 
  mutate(key = as_factor(key)) %>% 
  mutate(key=fct_relevel(key,c("crp>30", "10<crp<30", "crp<10"))) %>%
  group_by(value) %>% 
  mutate(percentage = n / sum(n) * 100)

ggplot(freq_table_long2, aes(x = value, y = percentage, 
                          stratum = key, fill = key,
                          alluvium = id)) +
  geom_stratum(alpha = .5) +
  geom_flow()+ 
  theme_minimal()

Exercises

Dataset

Dataset: tlc.csv

Description: The Treatment of Lead-Exposed Children (TLC) trial was a placebo-controlled, randomized study of succimer (a chelating agent) in 100 children with blood lead levels of 20-44 micrograms/dL.

Variables:

  • id a factor with 100 levels

  • trt - treatment arm ( placebo and succimer)

  • y0 to y6 - lead measurement over 6 weeks (baseline, week1, week4, week6)

 #Read the TLC datset
 tlc <- read.csv("https://www.dropbox.com/s/dj6ssrn3pmqtrnd/tlc.csv?dl=1")
 head(tlc)
  id trt   y0   y1   y4   y6
1  1   P 30.8 26.9 25.8 23.8
2  2   A 26.5 14.8 19.5 21.0
3  3   A 25.8 23.0 19.1 23.2
4  4   P 24.7 24.5 22.0 22.5
5  5   A 20.4  2.8  3.2  9.4
6  6   A 20.4  5.4  4.5 11.9
